<subSubSection lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="17" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,530,716]" box="[151,281,530,556]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Etymology</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,530,716]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
The species is named after Dr. Patrice Bouchard, curator of the 
<taxonomicName box="[965,1094,570,596]" class="Magnoliopsida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
collection of CNCI. Among the specimens loaned by CNCI, I found the first specimens of two new 
<taxonomicName box="[1037,1251,610,636]" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Scolytocis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1037,1156,610,635]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Scolytocis</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
described here (
<taxonomicName authority="Lopes-Andrade, 2008" authorityName="Lopes-Andrade" authorityYear="2008" box="[161,347,650,675]" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Scolytocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bouchardi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[161,347,650,675]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Scol. bouchardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[356,452,650,676]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[356,452,650,676]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Lopes-Andrade, 2008" authorityName="Lopes-Andrade" authorityYear="2008" box="[513,679,650,675]" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Scolytocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="howdeni" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[513,679,650,675]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Scol. howdeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[689,785,650,676]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[689,785,650,676]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
). The study of the remaining specimens will certainly enhance the current knowledge on the 
<taxonomicName box="[603,679,690,716]" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ciidae</taxonomicName>
taxonomy, mainly of the Neotropical fauna.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,770,956]" box="[151,268,770,796]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,770,956]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
The species belongs to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lopes-Andrade" authorityYear="2008" box="[516,635,810,835]" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Scolytocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bouchardi">
<emphasis box="[516,635,810,835]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">bouchardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group, due to the smooth posterior margin of pronotum and the triconcave prosternum. It differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Lopes-Andrade, 2008" authorityName="Lopes-Andrade" authorityYear="2008" box="[646,852,850,875]" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Scolytocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="difficillimus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[646,852,850,875]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Scol. difficillimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[860,953,850,876]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[860,953,850,876]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
by combination of the following characters: (i) width of eye usually more than 1.2X the basal width of scutellum; (ii) basal width of scutellum near 0.17X the greatest elytral width; (iii) Metatibiae less than 4X as long as broad.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1010,1876]" box="[151,288,1010,1036]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1010,1876]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<materialsCitation country="Mexico" location="Apex" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" specimenCount="6" stateProvince="Oaxaca" typeStatus="holotype">
<emphasis box="[198,313,1050,1075]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<typeStatus box="[198,309,1050,1075]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Holotype</typeStatus>
.
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[329,465,1050,1076]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–29" captionStartId="60.[151,269,1835,1859]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1811]" captionTargetId="figure-31@60.[151,1436,194,1811]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="FIGURES 27–29. Scolytocis bouchardi sp. nov. 27. Dorsal view. 28. Lateral view. 29. Ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127001/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Figs 27–29</figureCitation>
) Measurements in mm: TL 1.42; PL 0.47; PW 0.58; EL 0.89; EW 0.63; GD 0.58. Ratios: PL/PW 0.81; EL/EW 1.41; EL/PL 1.89; GD/EW 0.92; TL/EW 2.25. Body dark brown; head and pronotum darker than elytra, almost black; antennae, mouthparts and legs light yellowish brown. Head sparsely punctate, finely and inconspicuously microreticulate. Each antenna (
<figureCitation box="[1077,1188,1170,1196]" captionStart="FIGURES 63–65" captionStartId="72.[151,269,1404,1428]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1381]" captionTargetId="figure-85@72.[151,1436,194,1381]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 63–65. Antennae of the Northern Neotropical Scolytocis Blair. 63. Scol. bouchardi sp. nov. (A), Scol. cariborum sp. nov. (B), Scol. danielssoni sp. nov. (C). 64. Scol. difficillimus sp. nov. (A), Scol. howdeni sp. nov. (B), Scol. indecisus sp. nov. (C). 65. Scol. kiskeyensis sp. nov. (A), Scol. lawrencei sp. nov. (B), Scol. panamensis sp. nov. (C). First antennomere not shown in Scol. danielssoni sp. nov. (63C, asterisk)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127031" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127031/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 63A</figureCitation>
; 
<typeStatus box="[1203,1306,1170,1196]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">paratype</typeStatus>
) with nine antennomeres (FL 
<quantity box="[379,494,1210,1236]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.8" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="0.098">0.098mm</quantity>
; CL 
<quantity box="[557,672,1210,1236]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="0.17">0.170mm</quantity>
; CL/FL 1.74); length of the antennomeres (in mm) as follows: 0.088; 0.043; 0.048; 0.018; 0.015; 0.018; 0.045; 0.045; 0.080. Eyes with greatest width 1.28X the basal width of scutellum. Pronotum sparsely punctate; puncture fine, shallow, separated by a distance of two to four puncture widths; interstice between punctures inconspicuously, finely microreticulate; anterolateral margins slightly arched inwards; posterolateral angles broadly rounded; posterior margin without rugose border. Scutellum bearing small punctures near the anterior margin, interstice smooth and shiny; basal width 0.17X the EW. Elytral punctation subseriate; puncture coarser, shallower and more irregular than those of pronotum; interstice between punctures shiny, rugose, but not microreticulate; elytral apex subacute, with some sparse and small cuticular globules; apical region bearing a concavity. Each hindwing (
<figureCitation box="[1089,1176,1530,1556]" captionStart="FIGURES 54–56" captionStartId="69.[151,269,1344,1368]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1320]" captionTargetId="figure-37@69.[151,1436,194,1320]" captionTargetPageId="69" captionText="FIGURES 54–56. Hindwings of Northern Neotropical Scolytocis Blair. 54. Scol. bouchardi sp. nov. 55. Scol. cariborum sp. nov. 56. Scol. danielssoni sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127201" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127201/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 54</figureCitation>
; 
<typeStatus box="[1189,1291,1530,1556]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">paratype</typeStatus>
) with apical area bearing one vague, incomplete pigmented line near the anterior margin. Prosternum triconcave, without longitudinal carina at midline; surface shiny, rather smooth, with indistinct rugosity in high magnifications (&gt;100X). Metaventrite bearing small and sparse setae; discrimen one-fourth the length of metaventrite at midline. Abdominal ventrites bearing small and sparse setae. Each metatibia (
<figureCitation box="[1087,1203,1690,1716]" captionStart="FIGURES 66–68" captionStartId="73.[151,269,1404,1428]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1381]" captionTargetId="figure-72@73.[151,1436,194,1381]" captionTargetPageId="73" captionText="FIGURES 66–68. Metatibiae of the Northern Neotropical Scolytocis Blair. 66. Scol. bouchardi sp. nov. (A), Scol. cariborum sp. nov. (B), Scol. danielssoni sp. nov. (C). 67. Scol. difficillimus sp. nov. (A), Scol. howdeni sp. nov. (B), Scol. indecisus sp. nov. (C). 68. Scol. kiskeyensis sp. nov. (A), Scol. lawrencei sp. nov. (B), Scol. panamensis sp. nov. (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127033" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127033/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 66A</figureCitation>
, 
<typeStatus box="[1222,1325,1690,1716]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">paratype</typeStatus>
) broadly rounded, near 3.5X as long as broad; outer edge with spines (around 20) regularly distributed at basal two thirds and then getting sparser. 
<emphasis box="[516,878,1771,1796]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
Male genitalia (in a 
<typeStatus box="[756,865,1771,1796]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">paratype</typeStatus>
).
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[893,980,1770,1796]" captionStart="FIGURES 69–71" captionStartId="74.[151,269,1427,1451]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1403]" captionTargetId="figure-57@74.[151,1436,194,1403]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="FIGURES 69–71. Male genitalia of Scolytocis Blair showing the Y-shaped ninth segment (ix), basal piece (b.p), tegmen (teg) and penis (pen). 69. Scol. bouchardi sp. nov. 70. Scol. cariborum sp. nov. (ninth segment broken; see asterisks). 71. Scol. difficillimus sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127037" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127037/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 69</figureCitation>
, 
<typeStatus box="[992,1092,1770,1796]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">paratype</typeStatus>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[1164,1255,1770,1796]" country="Mexico" name="Oaxaca" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Oaxaca</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1266,1357,1770,1796]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Mexico</collectingCountry>
) 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:038E87B5FFBCCE60FF6A4BA8FD1BFA53:8EF86078FFBCCE7FFAA14C85FA5EF8F5" box="[1372,1435,1770,1796]" country="Mexico" name="Apex" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" stateProvince="Oaxaca">Apex</location>
of tegmen (sclerotized apical two-thirds) subtriangular; median lobe extremely membranous, elongate, near 1.5X longer than tegmen.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
